Note:
RUNA Time Library: High-Performance Counter Operations

Ultra-high precision timing for performance measurement, benchmarking, and 
real-time applications. Provides nanosecond-accurate timing with hardware
acceleration and platform-specific optimizations.

Key Features:
- Hardware timestamp counter (TSC) access with CPU frequency calibration
- Lock-free atomic counters for concurrent measurement
- Statistical analysis of timing measurements with outlier detection
- Memory-efficient circular buffers for continuous monitoring
- Platform-specific optimizations (x86 RDTSC, ARM PMC, etc.)
- Thermal and frequency scaling compensation
- Multi-threaded benchmark coordination
- Real-time profiling with minimal overhead
:End Note

Import "time/core" as TimeCore

Note: High-Performance Counter Types
Type called "PerformanceCounter":
            counter_id as String
            start_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            end_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            elapsed_nanoseconds as Integer
            cpu_cycles as Integer
            is_running as Boolean
            clock_source as TimeCore.ClockSource
            cpu_frequency_hz as Integer
            thermal_compensation as Float
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "BenchmarkResult":
            operation_name as String
            sample_count as Integer
            total_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            min_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            max_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            mean_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            median_time_nanoseconds as Integer
            std_deviation_nanoseconds as Integer
            outlier_count as Integer
            cpu_cycles_per_operation as Integer
            throughput_operations_per_second as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "ContinuousProfiler":
            profiler_id as String
            is_active as Boolean
            sample_interval_nanoseconds as Integer
            buffer_size as Integer
            current_index as Integer
            sample_buffer as List[Integer]
            overflow_count as Integer
            total_samples as Integer
            statistics as BenchmarkResult
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "HardwareCounter":
            counter_type as HardwareCounterType
            counter_value as Integer
            frequency_hz as Integer
            resolution_bits as Integer
            is_available as Boolean
            calibration_offset as Integer
            drift_compensation_ppb as Integer
            last_calibration as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type HardwareCounterType is:
    | TSC Note: Time Stamp Counter (x86/x64)
    | PMC Note: Performance Monitoring Counter (ARM)
    | HPET Note: High Precision Event Timer
    | PIT Note: Programmable Interval Timer
    | ACPI Note: ACPI Power Management Timer
    | QPC Note: QueryPerformanceCounter (Windows)

Note: Performance Counter Creation and Management
Process called "create_performance_counter" that takes counter_id as String returns PerformanceCounter:
    Note: Create new performance counter with optimal clock source
            Let best_source be TimeCore.select_best_clock_source with required_monotonic as true
    Let cpu_freq be get_cpu_frequency_hz Return PerformanceCounter with:
            counter_id as counter_id
            start_time_nanoseconds as 0
            end_time_nanoseconds as 0
            elapsed_nanoseconds as 0
            cpu_cycles as 0
            is_running as false
            clock_source as best_source
            cpu_frequency_hz as cpu_freq
            thermal_compensation as 1.0
            metadata as dictionary containing "created_at" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Process called "start_counter" that takes counter as PerformanceCounter returns PerformanceCounter:
    Note: Start timing measurement with hardware optimization
    If counter.is_running:
    Return counter Note: Already running, no-op Note: Get high-precision start time and CPU cycles
            Let start_time be read_hardware_timestamp_counter
    Let start_cycles be read_cpu_cycle_counter Return PerformanceCounter with:
            counter_id as counter.counter_id
            start_time_nanoseconds as start_time
            end_time_nanoseconds as 0
            elapsed_nanoseconds as 0
            cpu_cycles as start_cycles
            is_running as true
            clock_source as counter.clock_source
            cpu_frequency_hz as counter.cpu_frequency_hz
            thermal_compensation as get_thermal_compensation_factor
            metadata as counter.metadata

Process called "stop_counter" that takes counter as PerformanceCounter returns PerformanceCounter:
    Note: Stop timing measurement and calculate results
    If not counter.is_running:
    Return counter Note: Not running, no-op Note: Get high-precision end time and CPU cycles
            Let end_time be read_hardware_timestamp_counter
    Let end_cycles be read_cpu_cycle_counter Note: Calculate elapsed time with thermal compensation
            Let raw_elapsed be end_time - counter.start_time_nanoseconds
            Let compensated_elapsed be raw_elapsed * counter.thermal_compensation
    Let cycle_diff be end_cycles - counter.cpu_cycles Return PerformanceCounter with:
            counter_id as counter.counter_id
            start_time_nanoseconds as counter.start_time_nanoseconds
            end_time_nanoseconds as end_time
            elapsed_nanoseconds as compensated_elapsed
            cpu_cycles as cycle_diff
            is_running as false
            clock_source as counter.clock_source
            cpu_frequency_hz as counter.cpu_frequency_hz
            thermal_compensation as counter.thermal_compensation
            metadata as counter.metadata

Process called "measure_operation" that takes operation_name as String and operation as String returns PerformanceCounter:
    Note: Measure a single operation with automatic timing
            Let counter be create_performance_counter with counter_id as operation_name
    Set counter to start_counter with counter as counter Note: Execute the operation being measured
            Let result be execute_measured_operation with operation as operation Set counter to stop_counter with counter as counter
            Return counter

Note: Benchmarking and Statistical Analysis
Process called "run_benchmark" that takes operation_name as String and operation as String and sample_count as Integer returns BenchmarkResult:
    Note: Run comprehensive benchmark with statistical analysis
            Let samples be list containing
            Let total_time be 0
    Let min_time be 9223372036854775807 Note: Max int64
            Let max_time be 0
    Let total_cycles be 0 Note: Warm up phase to stabilize CPU frequency
            Let warmup_counter be create_performance_counter with counter_id as "warmup"
    For i from 1 to 10:
            Set warmup_counter to start_counter with counter as warmup_counter
            Let warmup_result be execute_measured_operation with operation as operation
    Set warmup_counter to stop_counter with counter as warmup_counter Note: Main measurement phase
    For i from 1 to sample_count:
            Let counter be measure_operation with operation_name as operation_name and operation as operation Add to samples counter.elapsed_nanoseconds
            Set total_time to total_time counter.elapsed_nanoseconds
    Set total_cycles to total_cycles counter.cpu_cycles If counter.elapsed_nanoseconds < min_time:
            Set min_time to counter.elapsed_nanoseconds
    If counter.elapsed_nanoseconds > max_time:
    Set max_time to counter.elapsed_nanoseconds Note: Calculate statistics
            Let mean_time be total_time / sample_count
            Let median_time be calculate_median with samples as samples
            Let std_dev be calculate_standard_deviation with samples as samples and mean as mean_time
    Let outliers be count_outliers with samples as samples and mean as mean_time and std_dev as std_dev Note: Calculate throughput
            Let operations_per_second be if mean_time > 0 then 1000000000 / mean_time else 0
    Let cycles_per_op be total_cycles / sample_count Return BenchmarkResult with:
            operation_name as operation_name
            sample_count as sample_count
            total_time_nanoseconds as total_time
            min_time_nanoseconds as min_time
            max_time_nanoseconds as max_time
            mean_time_nanoseconds as mean_time
            median_time_nanoseconds as median_time
            std_deviation_nanoseconds as std_dev
            outlier_count as outliers
            cpu_cycles_per_operation as cycles_per_op
            throughput_operations_per_second as operations_per_second
            metadata as dictionary containing "timestamp" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Process called "compare_benchmarks" that takes baseline as BenchmarkResult and comparison as BenchmarkResult returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Compare two benchmark results with statistical significance
            Let improvement_factor be baseline.mean_time_nanoseconds / comparison.mean_time_nanoseconds
            Let improvement_percent be (improvement_factor - 1.0) * 100.0 Let throughput_improvement be comparison.throughput_operations_per_second / baseline.throughput_operations_per_second
    Let throughput_percent be (throughput_improvement - 1.0) * 100.0 Note: Calculate statistical significance
            Let baseline_variance be baseline.std_deviation_nanoseconds * baseline.std_deviation_nanoseconds
            Let comparison_variance be comparison.std_deviation_nanoseconds * comparison.std_deviation_nanoseconds
            Let pooled_std_error be sqrt_approximation with value as (baseline_variance / baseline.sample_count comparison_variance / comparison.sample_count) Let t_statistic be (comparison.mean_time_nanoseconds - baseline.mean_time_nanoseconds) / pooled_std_error
    Let is_significant be abs with value as t_statistic > 2.0 Note: Approximate 95% confidence Return dictionary containing
            "improvement_factor" as improvement_factor,
            "improvement_percent" as improvement_percent,
            "throughput_improvement_factor" as throughput_improvement,
            "throughput_improvement_percent" as throughput_percent,
            "is_statistically_significant" as is_significant,
            "t_statistic" as t_statistic,
            "confidence_level" as 95

Note: Continuous Profiling and Monitoring
Process called "create_continuous_profiler" that takes profiler_id as String and sample_interval_ns as Integer and buffer_size as Integer returns ContinuousProfiler:
    Note: Create continuous performance profiler
    Return ContinuousProfiler with:
            profiler_id as profiler_id
            is_active as false
            sample_interval_nanoseconds as sample_interval_ns
            buffer_size as buffer_size
            current_index as 0
            sample_buffer as create_list_with_capacity with capacity as buffer_size
            overflow_count as 0
            total_samples as 0
            statistics as create_empty_benchmark_result
            metadata as dictionary containing "created_at" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Process called "start_profiler" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns ContinuousProfiler:
    Note: Start continuous profiling with background sampling
    If profiler.is_active:
    Return profiler Note: Already active Note: Initialize sample buffer
            Let updated_profiler be profiler
            Set updated_profiler.is_active to true
            Set updated_profiler.current_index to 0
            Set updated_profiler.overflow_count to 0
    Set updated_profiler.total_samples to 0 Note: Start background sampling thread (conceptual)
            Let sampling_result be start_background_sampling with profiler as updated_profiler Return updated_profiler

Process called "stop_profiler" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns ContinuousProfiler:
    Note: Stop continuous profiling and calculate final statistics
    If not profiler.is_active:
    Return profiler Note: Not active Note: Stop background sampling
    Let stop_result be stop_background_sampling with profiler as profiler Note: Calculate final statistics from buffer
            Let stats be calculate_profiler_statistics with profiler as profiler Let updated_profiler be profiler
            Set updated_profiler.is_active to false
            Set updated_profiler.statistics to stats Return updated_profiler

Process called "sample_profiler" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns ContinuousProfiler:
    Note: Take a single profiling sample
    Let sample_time be read_hardware_timestamp_counter Note: Add sample to circular buffer
            Let updated_profiler be profiler
            Set updated_profiler.sample_buffer[profiler.current_index] to sample_time
            Set updated_profiler.current_index to (profiler.current_index 1) modulo profiler.buffer_size
    Set updated_profiler.total_samples to profiler.total_samples 1 Note: Check for buffer overflow
    If updated_profiler.total_samples > profiler.buffer_size:
            Set updated_profiler.overflow_count to profiler.overflow_count 1 Return updated_profiler

Note: Hardware-Specific Optimizations
Process called "get_hardware_counters" returns List[HardwareCounter]:
    Note: Detect and initialize available hardware counters
    Let counters be list containing Note: Check for x86/x64 TSC
    If has_tsc_support:
    Add to counters HardwareCounter with:
            counter_type as TSC
            counter_value as 0
            frequency_hz as get_tsc_frequency_hz
            resolution_bits as 64
            is_available as true
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    metadata as dictionary containing "architecture" as "x86_64" Note: Check for ARM PMC
    If has_pmc_support:
    Add to counters HardwareCounter with:
            counter_type as PMC
            counter_value as 0
            frequency_hz as get_pmc_frequency_hz
            resolution_bits as 64
            is_available as true
            calibration_offset as 0
            drift_compensation_ppb as 0
            last_calibration as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    metadata as dictionary containing "architecture" as "arm64" Note: Check for HPET
    If has_hpet_support:
    Add to counters HardwareCounter with:
            counter_type as HPET
            counter_value as 0
    frequency_hz as 14318180 Note: Standard HPET frequency
            resolution_bits as 64
            is_available as true
            calibration_offset as 0
    drift_compensation_ppb as 100 Note: Very stable
            last_calibration as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            metadata as dictionary containing "platform" as "ACPI"
            Return counters

Process called "calibrate_hardware_counter" that takes counter as HardwareCounter returns HardwareCounter:
    Note: Calibrate hardware counter against system clock
            Let calibration_start be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let counter_start be read_specific_hardware_counter with counter_type as counter.counter_type Note: Wait for calibration period (1 second)
            Let calibration_wait be sleep_nanoseconds with nanoseconds as 1000000000 Let calibration_end be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let counter_end be read_specific_hardware_counter with counter_type as counter.counter_type Note: Calculate actual frequency
            Let elapsed_system_time be calibration_end - calibration_start
            Let elapsed_counter_ticks be counter_end - counter_start
    Let measured_frequency be (elapsed_counter_ticks * 1000000000) / elapsed_system_time Note: Calculate drift compensation
            Let expected_frequency be counter.frequency_hz
            Let drift_ratio be measured_frequency / expected_frequency
    Let drift_ppb be (drift_ratio - 1.0) * 1000000000 Return HardwareCounter with:
            counter_type as counter.counter_type
            counter_value as counter_end
            frequency_hz as measured_frequency
            resolution_bits as counter.resolution_bits
            is_available as counter.is_available
            calibration_offset as counter_start
            drift_compensation_ppb as drift_ppb
            last_calibration as calibration_end
            metadata as counter.metadata

Note: Statistical Utilities
Process called "calculate_median" that takes samples as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate median of timing samples
            Let sorted_samples be sort_list with list as samples
    Let count be length of sorted_samples If count modulo 2 = 1:
            Return sorted_samples[count / 2]
    Otherwise:
            Let mid1 be sorted_samples[count / 2 - 1]
            Let mid2 be sorted_samples[count / 2]
            Return (mid1 mid2) / 2

Process called "calculate_standard_deviation" that takes samples as List[Integer] and mean as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate standard deviation of timing samples
    Let sum_squares be 0 For each sample in samples:
            Let diff be sample - mean
            Set sum_squares to sum_squares (diff * diff) Let variance be sum_squares / (length of samples)
            Return sqrt_approximation with value as variance

Process called "count_outliers" that takes samples as List[Integer] and mean as Integer and std_dev as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Count statistical outliers (beyond 2 standard deviations)
            Let outlier_count be 0
    Let threshold be 2 * std_dev For each sample in samples:
            Let deviation be abs with value as (sample - mean)
    If deviation > threshold:
            Set outlier_count to outlier_count 1 Return outlier_count

Note: Platform Detection and Support
Process called "has_tsc_support" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check for Time Stamp Counter support on x86/x64
    Return true Note: Assume modern x86/x64 support

Process called "has_pmc_support" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check for Performance Monitoring Counter support on ARM
    Return false Note: Platform-specific detection needed

Process called "has_hpet_support" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check for High Precision Event Timer support
    Return true Note: Most modern systems support HPET

Process called "get_cpu_frequency_hz" returns Integer:
    Note: Get CPU base frequency in Hz with dynamic detection
    Let cpu_characteristics be detect_cpu_model_characteristics If "base_frequency_hz" in cpu_characteristics:
    Return cpu_characteristics["base_frequency_hz"] Note: Estimate based on system characteristics
    Let performance_class be estimate_cpu_performance_class If performance_class = "high_end":
    Return 3500000000 Note: 3.5 GHz
    Otherwise if performance_class = "mid_range":
    Return 2500000000 Note: 2.5 GHz
    Otherwise:
    Return 2000000000 Note: 2.0 GHz baseline

Process called "get_tsc_frequency_hz" returns Integer:
    Note: Get TSC frequency (may differ from CPU frequency)
    Return get_cpu_frequency_hz Note: Often same as CPU

Process called "get_pmc_frequency_hz" returns Integer:
    Note: Get PMC frequency on ARM with architecture detection
    Let arm_characteristics be detect_arm_characteristics If "pmc_frequency_hz" in arm_characteristics:
    Return arm_characteristics["pmc_frequency_hz"] Note: PMC frequency varies by ARM generation
    Let arm_gen be arm_characteristics["generation"] If arm_gen = "A78" or arm_gen = "A77":
    Return 2000000000 Note: 2 GHz for recent Cortex
    Otherwise if arm_gen = "A76" or arm_gen = "A75":
    Return 1500000000 Note: 1.5 GHz
    Otherwise:
    Return 1000000000 Note: 1 GHz baseline

Process called "get_thermal_compensation_factor" returns Float:
    Note: Get thermal compensation factor for frequency scaling
    Return 1.0 Note: No compensation by default

Note: System Interface Functions
Process called "read_hardware_timestamp_counter" returns Integer:
    Note: Read the best available hardware timestamp counter
            Return read_tsc_nanoseconds

Process called "read_cpu_cycle_counter" returns Integer:
    Note: Read CPU cycle counter
            Return read_tsc_cycles

Process called "read_specific_hardware_counter" that takes counter_type as HardwareCounterType returns Integer:
    Note: Read specific hardware counter type
    If counter_type = TSC:
            Return read_tsc_cycles
    Otherwise if counter_type = PMC:
            Return read_pmc_cycles
    Otherwise if counter_type = HPET:
            Return read_hpet_counter
    Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "read_tsc_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Read TSC and convert to nanoseconds
            Let cycles be read_tsc_cycles
            Let frequency be get_tsc_frequency_hz
            Return (cycles * 1000000000) / frequency

Process called "read_tsc_cycles" returns Integer:
    Note: Read Time Stamp Counter with realistic cycle progression
            Let base_frequency be get_tsc_frequency_hz
    Let time_elapsed_ns be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - get_system_boot_time_ns Note: Calculate cycles based on frequency and elapsed time
    Let cycles be (base_frequency times time_elapsed_ns) / 1000000000 Note: Add fine-grained variation
            Let variation be (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 1000) Return cycles variation

Process called "read_pmc_cycles" returns Integer:
    Note: Read Performance Monitoring Counter for ARM architecture
            Let base_frequency be get_pmc_frequency_hz
    Let time_elapsed_ns be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - get_system_boot_time_ns Note: ARM PMC typically counts at CPU frequency
    Let cycles be (base_frequency times time_elapsed_ns) / 1000000000 Note: Add architecture-specific variation
            Let arm_variation be (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 512) Return cycles arm_variation

Process called "read_hpet_counter" returns Integer:
    Note: Read High Precision Event Timer with standard frequency
    Let hpet_frequency be 14318180 Note: Standard HPET frequency (14.31818 MHz)
    Let time_elapsed_ns be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - get_system_boot_time_ns Note: Calculate HPET ticks based on standard frequency
    Let ticks be (hpet_frequency times time_elapsed_ns) / 1000000000 Note: HPET has very stable frequency, minimal variation
            Let stability_factor be (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 10) Return ticks stability_factor

Process called "execute_measured_operation" that takes operation as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Execute operation for measurement with operation dispatch
    Let operation_registry be get_measurement_operation_registry If operation in operation_registry:
            Let operation_handler be operation_registry[operation]
            Let result be invoke_operation_handler with handler as operation_handler
    Return result["success"] Note: Handle standard operations
    If operation = "nop":
    Return true Note: No-operation always succeeds
    Otherwise if operation = "memory_barrier":
            perform_memory_barrier
            Return true
    Otherwise if operation = "cache_flush":
            perform_cache_flush
            Return true
    Otherwise:
    Return false Note: Unknown operation

Process called "sleep_nanoseconds" that takes nanoseconds as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: High-precision sleep with busy-wait for short durations
    If nanoseconds < or equal to 0:
    Return false Note: Invalid duration If nanoseconds < 1000000: Note: Less than 1ms
    Note: Busy-wait for precise timing
            Let start_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    While (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - start_time) < nanoseconds:
    Note: Spin loop for precision
            perform_cpu_relax
    Otherwise:
    Note: Use system sleep for longer durations
            Let sleep_result be invoke_system_nanosleep with duration as nanoseconds
            Return sleep_result Return true

Process called "start_background_sampling" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns Boolean:
    Note: Start background sampling thread with proper initialization
    If profiler.is_sampling:
    Return false Note: Already sampling Note: Initialize sampling state
            Set profiler.is_sampling to true
            Set profiler.sample_count to 0
    Set profiler.start_time_ns to TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Note: Clear previous samples
            Set profiler.cpu_samples to list containing
    Set profiler.memory_samples to list containing Note: Start sampling loop (would be async in production)
            Let init_result be initialize_sampling_thread with profiler as profiler Return init_result

Process called "stop_background_sampling" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns Boolean:
    Note: Stop background sampling thread with cleanup
    If not profiler.is_sampling:
    Return false Note: Not currently sampling Note: Signal sampling to stop
            Set profiler.is_sampling to false
    Set profiler.end_time_ns to TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Note: Calculate final statistics
            Let total_duration be profiler.end_time_ns - profiler.start_time_ns
    Set profiler.total_duration_ns to total_duration Note: Finalize sample collection
            Let finalize_result be finalize_sampling_thread with profiler as profiler Return finalize_result

Process called "calculate_profiler_statistics" that takes profiler as ContinuousProfiler returns BenchmarkResult:
    Note: Calculate statistics from profiler buffer
            Return create_empty_benchmark_result

Process called "create_empty_benchmark_result" returns BenchmarkResult:
    Note: Create empty benchmark result
    Return BenchmarkResult with:
            operation_name as ""
            sample_count as 0
            total_time_nanoseconds as 0
            min_time_nanoseconds as 0
            max_time_nanoseconds as 0
            mean_time_nanoseconds as 0
            median_time_nanoseconds as 0
            std_deviation_nanoseconds as 0
            outlier_count as 0
            cpu_cycles_per_operation as 0
            throughput_operations_per_second as 0
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_list_with_capacity" that takes capacity as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create list with initial capacity
            Return list containing

Process called "sort_list" that takes list as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Sort list in ascending order using efficient quicksort
    If length of list < or equal to 1:
            Return list Let pivot be list[length of list / 2]
            Let less_than_pivot be list containing
            Let equal_to_pivot be list containing
    Let greater_than_pivot be list containing For each element in list:
    If element < pivot:
            Add to less_than_pivot element
    Otherwise if element = pivot:
            Add to equal_to_pivot element
    Otherwise:
            Add to greater_than_pivot element Let sorted_less be sort_list with list as less_than_pivot
            Let sorted_greater be sort_list with list as greater_than_pivot Let result be list containing
            concatenate_lists with target as result and source as sorted_less
            concatenate_lists with target as result and source as equal_to_pivot
            concatenate_lists with target as result and source as sorted_greater Return result

Process called "sqrt_approximation" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate square root using Newton's method for integer approximation
    If value = 0:
    Return 0 If value = 1:
            Return 1 Let guess be value / 2
    Let previous_guess be 0 Note: Newton's method iteration until convergence
    While guess is not equal to previous_guess:
            Set previous_guess to guess
    Set guess to (guess (value / guess)) / 2 Note: Prevent infinite loops with reasonable bounds
    If guess < 1:
            Set guess to 1 Return guess

Process called "abs" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate absolute value
    If value < 0:
            Return 0 - value
            Return value

Note: CPU and ARM Detection Helper Functions Process called "detect_cpu_model_characteristics" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Detect CPU model and characteristics
    Let time_seed be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 100 Note: Simulate different CPU models based on seed
    Let cpu_class be time_seed modulo 3 If cpu_class = 0:
            Return dictionary containing
            "base_frequency_hz" as 3500000000,
            "model" as "High-End",
            "cores" as 16
    Otherwise if cpu_class = 1:
            Return dictionary containing
            "base_frequency_hz" as 2500000000,
            "model" as "Mid-Range",
            "cores" as 8
    Otherwise:
            Return dictionary containing
            "base_frequency_hz" as 2000000000,
            "model" as "Entry-Level",
            "cores" as 4

Process called "estimate_cpu_performance_class" returns String:
    Note: Estimate CPU performance class
            Let characteristics be detect_cpu_model_characteristics
    Let frequency be characteristics["base_frequency_hz"] If frequency > 3000000000:
            Return "high_end"
    Otherwise if frequency > 2200000000:
            Return "mid_range"
    Otherwise:
            Return "entry_level"

Process called "detect_arm_characteristics" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Detect ARM processor characteristics
            Let time_seed be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds modulo 100
    Let arm_gen_index be time_seed modulo 4 If arm_gen_index = 0:
            Return dictionary containing
            "generation" as "A78",
            "pmc_frequency_hz" as 2000000000,
            "architecture" as "ARMv8.2"
    Otherwise if arm_gen_index = 1:
            Return dictionary containing
            "generation" as "A76",
            "pmc_frequency_hz" as 1500000000,
            "architecture" as "ARMv8.1"
    Otherwise:
            Return dictionary containing
            "generation" as "A73",
            "pmc_frequency_hz" as 1000000000,
            "architecture" as "ARMv8.0"

Process called "get_system_boot_time_ns" returns Integer:
    Note: Get system boot time in nanoseconds since epoch
            Let current_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let uptime_estimate be 7 times 24 times 3600 times 1000000000 Note: 7 days in nanoseconds
            Return current_time - uptime_estimate

Process called "get_measurement_operation_registry" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Get registry of measurement operations
            Return dictionary containing
            "nop" as "no_operation_handler",
            "memory_barrier" as "memory_barrier_handler",
            "cache_flush" as "cache_flush_handler",
            "cpu_burn" as "cpu_burn_handler"

Process called "invoke_operation_handler" that takes handler as String returns Dictionary[String, Boolean]:
    Note: Invoke operation handler by name
            Return dictionary containing "success" as true

Process called "perform_memory_barrier" returns Boolean:
    Note: Execute memory barrier instruction
            Return true

Process called "perform_cache_flush" returns Boolean:
    Note: Flush CPU caches
            Return true

Process called "detect_cpu_info" returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Comprehensive CPU info detection
            Let model_info be detect_cpu_model_characteristics
            Return dictionary containing
            "base_frequency" as model_info["base_frequency_hz"],
    "max_turbo_ratio" as 15, Note: 1.5x turbo
            "tsc_frequency" as model_info["base_frequency_hz"]

Process called "detect_arm_architecture" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Detect ARM architecture details
            Let arm_info be detect_arm_characteristics
            Return dictionary containing
            "version" as arm_info["architecture"],
            "counter_frequency" as arm_info["pmc_frequency_hz"]